wizard.aws.accessKey.label: Access key ID
wizard.aws.accessKey.popoverBody: You can create and find existing Access key IDs on the Identity and Access Management (IAM) page in the AWS console.
wizard.aws.bucket.label: Amazon S3 bucket
wizard.aws.bucket.popoverBody: Provide the S3 bucket name to which the image file will be uploaded before being imported into EC2. The bucket must already exist in the Region where you want to import your image. You can find a list of buckets on the S3 buckets page in the Amazon S3 storage service in the AWS console.
wizard.aws.imageName.label: Image name
wizard.aws.imageName.popoverBody: Provide a file name to be used for the image file that will be uploaded.
wizard.aws.region.label: AWS region
wizard.aws.region.popoverBody: Provide the AWS Region where you want to import your image. This must be the same region where the S3 bucket exists.
wizard.aws.secretAccessKey.label: Secret access key
wizard.aws.secretAccessKey.popoverBody: You can view the Secret access key only when you create a new Access key ID on the Identity and Access Management (IAM) page in the AWS console.
wizard.aws.title: Upload to AWS
wizard.azure.imageName.label: Image name
wizard.azure.imageName.popoverBody: Provide a file name to be used for the image file that will be uploaded.
wizard.azure.storageAccessKey.label: Storage access key
wizard.azure.storageAccessKey.popoverBod: Provide the access key for the desired storage account. You can find the access key on the Access keys page of the storage account. You can find storage accounts on the Storage accounts page in the Azure portal.
wizard.azure.storageAccount.label: Storage account
wizard.azure.storageAccount.popoverBody: Provide the name of a storage account. You can find storage accounts on the Storage accounts page in the Azure portal.
wizard.azure.storageContainer.label: Storage container
wizard.azure.storageContainer.popoverBod: Provide the Blob container to which the image file will be uploaded. You can find containers under the Blob service section of a storage account. You can find storage accounts on the Storage accounts page in the Azure portal.
wizard.azure.title: Upload to Azure
wizard.blueprintName.name: blueprint
wizard.blueprintName.popover.content: This process can take a while. Images are built in the order they are started.
wizard.customizations.hostname.helperTex: If no hostname is provided, the hostname will be determined by the OS.
wizard.customizations.hostname.label: Hostname
wizard.customizations.hostname.validatio: Valid characters are letters from a to z, the digits from 0 to 9, and the hyphen (-). A hostname may not start with a hyphen. Each element of the hostname must be from 1 to 63 characters long and the entire hostname can be at most 253 characters long.

wizard.imageOutput.imageSize.label: Image Size
wizard.imageOutput.imageSize.popoverBody: Set the size that you want the image to be when instantiated. The total package size and target destination of your image should be considered when setting the image size.
wizard.imageOutput.title: Image output
wizard.imageOutput.uploadAWS.popoverBody: Image Builder can upload images you create to an S3 bucket in AWS and then import them into EC2. When the image build is complete and the upload action is successful, the image file is available in the AMI section of EC2. Most of the values required to upload the image can be found in the {console}. {br}{br}This upload process requires that you have an Identity and Access Management (IAM) role named {vmimport} to ensure that the image can be imported from the S3 bucket into EC2. For more details, refer to the {role}.
wizard.imageOutput.uploadAzure.popoverBo: Image Builder can upload images you create to a Blob container in {azure}. When the image build is complete and the upload action is successful, the image file is available in the Storage account and Blob container that you specified.
wizard.imageOutput.uploadOCI.popoverBody: Image Builder can upload images you create to an OCI bucket in OCI and register it as a custom image. When the image build is complete and the upload action is successful, the image should be available under custom images. Most of the values required to upload the image can be found in the {console}.{br}{br}This upload process requires that you have an Identity and Access Management (IAM) with attached policy to manage custom images to ensure that the image can be imported as a custom image from the bucket. For more details, refer to the {policy}.
wizard.imageOutput.uploadVMWare.popoverB: Image Builder can upload images you create to VMWare vSphere. When the image build is complete and the upload action is successful, the image file is available in the Cluster on the vSphere instance that you specified.
wizard.oci.bucket.label: OCI bucket
wizard.oci.bucket.popoverBody: Provide the bucket name to which the image file will be uploaded before being imported as a custom image. The bucket must already exist in the Region where you want to import your image. You can find a list of buckets on the OCI buckets page in the OCI storage service in the OCI console.
wizard.oci.bucketCompartment.label: Bucket compartment
wizard.oci.bucketNamespace.label: Bucket namespace
wizard.oci.bucketRegion.label: Bucket region
wizard.oci.bucketTenancy.label: Bucket tenancy
wizard.oci.compartment.popoverBody: Provide the compartment of the OCI bucket compartment your uploading to. You can find the compartment in the bucket details.
wizard.oci.fingerprint.label: Fingerprint
wizard.oci.fingerprint.popoverBody: You can view your deployed RSA keys fingerprint in the API Keys section on the Identity and Access Management (IAM) page in the OCI console.
wizard.oci.imageName.label: Image name
wizard.oci.imageName.popoverBody: Provide a file name to be used for the image file that will be uploaded.
wizard.oci.namespace.popoverBody: Provide the namespace of the OCI bucket your uploading to. You can find the namespace in the bucket details.
wizard.oci.privateKey.label: Private key
wizard.oci.privateKey.popoverBody: You can view your deployed RSA keys in the API Keys section on the Identity and Access Management (IAM) page in the OCI console.
wizard.oci.region.popoverBody: Provide the region of the Bucket region your uploading to. You can find the region in the bucket details.
wizard.oci.tenancy.popoverBody: Provide the tenancy of the OCI bucket your uploading to. You can find the tenancy in the bucket details.
wizard.oci.title: Upload to OCI
wizard.oci.userOCID.label: User OCID
wizard.oci.userOCID.popoverBody: You can find your user OCID Identity and Access Management (IAM) page in the OCI console.
wizard.ostree.parentCommit.label: Parent
wizard.ostree.parentCommit.popoverBody: Provide the commit id or ref of the parent in the repository for which this commit provides an update. If no parent is specified it will be inferred from the user-defined ref.
wizard.ostree.ref.helpText: Valid characters for ref are letters from a to z, the digits from 0 to 9, the hyphen (-), the underscore (_), the period (.), and the forward slash (/). A ref must start with a letter, a number, or an underscore. Slashes must also be followed by a letter or number.
wizard.ostree.ref.label: Ref
wizard.ostree.ref.popoverBody: Provide the name of the branch for the content. If the ref does not already exist it will be created. If the ref is not specified, the default ref for the distro will be used.
wizard.ostree.repoURL.label: Repository URL
wizard.ostree.repoURL.popoverBody: Provide the URL of the upstream repository. This repository is where the parent OSTree commit will be pulled from.
wizard.ostree.title: OSTree settings
wizard.ostree.validationError: Either the parent commit or repository url can be specified. Not both.
